    title: "The Hollowing",
    description: "After moving into her late grandmother's house, Mia discovers that the walls contain a presence that feeds on memories. As the entity strips away her recollections one by one, she must solve the mystery of her grandmother's death before she forgets everything.",
    fullContent: "# Chapter 1: The Inheritance\n\nMia had always known the house on Birchwood Lane was wrong. As a child visiting her grandmother, she had felt eyes watching from the corners, heard whispers in the walls that sounded like voices trying to remember something important. Now her grandmother was dead, and the house was hers.\n\nThe first night, Mia woke to find all the family photographs turned face-down. She assumed it was her doing, a late-night indiscretion she couldn't recall. But the next morning, she found more than photographs. The house had rearranged itself. Furniture had moved to different rooms, doors that led to closets now opened onto hallways, and the basement had an extra door that shouldn't have existed.\n\nMia tried to rationalize the changes, blaming stress and grief. But when she woke to discover she couldn't remember her mother's name, she knew something was deeply wrong. The house was doing something to her mind, and she had to understand what before it was too late.\n\n# Chapter 2: The Presence\n\nThe presence made itself known gradually. Mia would catch glimpses of movement in peripheral vision, a shadow that moved against the light, a figure that vanished when she turned to look. The whispers grew louder, forming words she almost understood but couldn't quite grasp.\n\nShe found her grandmother's journals hidden in the walls, placed there for someone to find. The entries described the same experiences, the moving furniture, the altered rooms, the progressive loss of memory. Her grandmother had documented her descent into confusion with scientific precision, recording each lost memory like a patient chart.\n\nThe journals revealed the truth. The house contained an entity that fed on human memories, drawing sustenance from the recollections that defined its victims. It had been dormant for decades, preserved in the walls like a spider in its web. Now that Mia had returned, it was waking up and feeding.\n\n# Chapter 3: The History\n\nMia's research uncovered the house's dark history. Built in 1887 by a physician named Dr. Elias Thorne, it had been designed as a sanitarium for patients with memory disorders. Thorne believed that memories had physical substance, that they could be extracted and preserved. His experiments created the entity, a being born from stolen recollections.\n\nThe entity was not evil in the traditional sense. It was simply hungry, a creature of appetite that had been created by human hubris. It fed on memories because that was all it knew. The accumulated experiences of its victims were its only sustenance. Without them, it would cease to exist.\n\nMia realized that her grandmother had known about the entity and had chosen to live with it, feeding it small memories to keep it dormant. Her death had disrupted the arrangement, and now the entity was starving. Mia had to find a way to satisfy its hunger without losing herself completely.\n\n# Chapter 4: The Descent\n\nThe entity's attacks grew more aggressive. Mia lost entire days, waking to find evidence of activities she couldn't remember. She discovered she had signed legal documents, made phone calls to people she didn't recognize, and written letters to friends she had forgotten she had.\n\nShe fought back by creating external memory systems, written records, video diaries, notes hidden throughout the house. Each note was a message to her future self, a lifeline to hold onto when the entity stripped away her recollections. The strategy worked temporarily, but the entity adapted, targeting the systems themselves.\n\nThe breakthrough came when Mia discovered that the entity could be satisfied with specific types of memories, traumatic ones that the mind naturally wanted to forget. Her grandmother had been feeding it her worst experiences, using the entity as a kind of psychological purging. Mia could do the same, offering her darkest memories while preserving her most precious ones.\n\n# Chapter 5: The Resolution\n\nMia made a deal with the entity. She would provide it with her traumatic memories, the painful experiences that weighed her down, while keeping the memories that defined her. It was a delicate balance, requiring her to confront her worst moments while protecting her most cherished ones.\n\nThe entity accepted the arrangement, recognizing Mia's intelligence and compassion. It revealed that it had been trying to communicate with her grandmother, not to harm her but to negotiate. The whispers in the walls had been its attempts at conversation, distorted by the limitations of its existence.\n\nMia remained in the house on Birchwood Lane, becoming its guardian as her grandmother had been. She learned to live with the entity, understanding it as a part of the house's ecosystem. The horror had not disappeared. It had been transformed into something she could manage, a relationship with a creature that had never asked to exist. Some houses, she learned, are alive, and they need caretakers who understand their hunger.",
