    title: "The Collector",
    description: "Antique dealer Simon purchases a storage unit containing objects from an asylum that closed in 1952. Each object contains the trapped spirit of a former patient, and Simon must decide whether to free them or sell them to collectors who prize supernatural artifacts.",
    fullContent: "# Chapter 1: The Purchase\n\nSimon had been buying storage units for fifteen years, developing an instinct for finding treasures among the junk. So when the contents of an abandoned unit from the Willowbrook State Hospital went up for auction, he placed his bid without hesitation. The unit contained furniture, medical equipment, and personal belongings that could fetch a fortune from the right buyers.\n\nThe first night, Simon heard whispers coming from the boxes. He assumed it was the wind, the building settling, his imagination. But when he opened a box of personal effects and found a music box that played by itself, he knew something was wrong. The music box played a melody he had never heard, beautiful and haunting, that made him feel like he was being watched.\n\nHe researched Willowbrook State Hospital and discovered it had been a facility for patients with severe mental illness, closed after allegations of abuse and neglect. The patients had been transferred elsewhere, but their personal belongings had been left behind. Simon realized that some of those patients might still be present, trapped in the objects they had loved.\n\n# Chapter 2: The Spirits\n\nThe spirits made contact one by one. A little girl appeared in mirrors, her face pale and accusing. An elderly man sat in a rocking chair that hadn't been there before, his eyes following Simon's movements. A young woman sang lullabies in the hallway, her voice echoing through empty rooms.\n\nSimon was terrified but fascinated. He had always believed in the supernatural but had never experienced it directly. The spirits were not threatening. They seemed confused, lost, unable to understand what had happened to them. They had been patients at Willowbrook, trapped when the hospital closed, bound to the objects that had given them comfort in life.\n\nEach spirit had a story. The little girl had been abandoned by her parents and died of influenza in 1948. The elderly man had been a professor before his illness, his mind preserved in fragments within his favorite books. The young woman had been a musician, her talent recognized too late to save her. Simon listened to their stories and felt their pain.\n\n# Chapter 3: The Offer\n\nWord of Simon's discovery reached other collectors, people who prized supernatural artifacts for their rarity and power. One collector, a wealthy woman named Cassandra, offered a fortune for the objects containing spirits. She planned to display them in her private museum, where the spirits would be trapped forever.\n\nSimon was tempted by the money but troubled by the morality. The spirits were people, not objects. Selling them felt like a betrayal of the trust they had placed in him. But he also knew that freeing them might not be possible. He had no experience with spiritual liberation.\n\nThe spirits reacted to Cassandra's offer with terror. They showed Simon visions of their past, the suffering they had endured at Willowbrook, the hope they had felt when the hospital closed. They believed Simon would free them, not sell them. Their faith made his decision harder.\n\n# Chapter 4: The Ritual\n\nSimon sought help from a spiritual practitioner named Elena, who agreed to assist with freeing the spirits. The ritual required each spirit to confront the trauma that had bound them to the physical world. It was painful work, requiring the reliving of memories that had been suppressed for decades.\n\nThe little girl's spirit was the most difficult. She had never understood why her parents had left her, and the question had haunted her for seventy years. Simon held her hand as Elena guided her through the memories, finding the truth that had been hidden. Her parents hadn't abandoned her. They had died in an accident, and no one had told her.\n\nThe release was beautiful and terrible. Each spirit ascended in a burst of light, their faces showing peace for the first time since Simon had known them. The objects grew cold and ordinary, empty of the life they had contained. Simon wept, feeling the loss of companions he had never expected to have.\n\n# Chapter 5: The Aftermath\n\nWith the spirits freed, Simon's business changed. He no longer sought supernatural artifacts. The experience had taught him that some things shouldn't be bought or sold. Instead, he became an advocate for the ethical treatment of spiritual beings, arguing that they deserved the same rights as the living.\n\nCassandra was furious at losing her potential acquisitions. She sued Simon for breach of contract, but the case was dismissed when the court ruled that spiritual entities couldn't be property. The ruling set a precedent that would change the way the world viewed the supernatural.\n\nSimon continued his work as an antique dealer, but now with a new purpose. He searched for objects that contained trapped spirits, working with Elena to free them. The work was its own reward, the gratitude of released spirits, the knowledge that he was making a difference, the understanding that some collections are better left incomplete. He had learned that the most valuable antiques are the ones you let go.",
